Context (ID: PubMedQA-17343208): Sickle cell disease (SCD) is a group of hereditary red blood cell disorders characterized by a structural change in the hemoglobin beta chain. It is one of the most common genetic diseases worldwide, particularly in sub-Saharan Africa. In SCD, the hemoglobin beta chain is substituted by an abnormal form of the beta chain called HbS (sickle-shaped), which causes red blood cells to take on the shape of a sickle. This reduces the blood oxygen transport capacity and promotes sickling. Sickling leads to vascular occlusion, tissue damage, and infarction in different organs. The most common complications of SCD are acute vaso-occlusive crises (VOCs), in which VOCs can lead to acute chest syndrome. Acute chest syndrome is the leading cause of mortality in patients with SCD. The risk of acute chest syndrome increases with age and is the leading cause of mortality in patients with SCD. Acute chest syndrome is characterized by hemoptysis, pleuritic chest pain, and shortness of breath. The diagnosis of acute chest syndrome is based on the presence of new pulmonary infiltrates on chest X-rays. The treatment of acute chest syndrome includes oxygen therapy, blood transfusion, analgesics, and corticosteroids.
